I’ve been a journalist for eight years, and this is the first time I’ve seen Sudanese willing to do this.
You can’t be a journalist when you have to control your words, your thoughts and your choice of subjects.
The mass protests started out in the provinces in December, and by Christmas they had reached Khartoum.
The army establishment, which has ruled contemporary Sudan since independence in 1956, has repeatedly staged coups against democratically elected governments.
Yet over the past 10 days, we have been living through a remarkable flowering of freedom of expression.